<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>⚔️ RS001 Week 11 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Strategy — Fight or Think? · <strong>Course:</strong> Text Adventure (Python) · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week you think about code that lets the player solve a problem in more than one way. A menu of actions — fight, think, run — leads to a different result for each choice. The <strong>order</strong> of your <code>if</code> / <code>elif</code> / <code>else</code> decides which result wins. Read the code, predict what it does, and get ready to explain it in your own words.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>🧠 Words to know: <strong>action</strong>, <strong>menu</strong>, <strong>elif</strong>, <strong>else</strong>, <strong>outcome</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<pre><code class="language-python">action = game.ask(&quot;Fight or think?&quot;).strip().lower()
if action == &quot;fight&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You swing your sword!&quot;)
elif action == &quot;think&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You spot the enemy's weakness!&quot;)
else:
    game.say(&quot;You hesitate and get hit!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. Run it in your head and write what you think happens.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">action = &quot;think&quot;
if action == &quot;fight&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;attack&quot;)
elif action == &quot;think&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;clever&quot;)
else:
    game.say(&quot;oops&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Which word is printed?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">action = &quot;dance&quot;
if action == &quot;fight&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;attack&quot;)
elif action == &quot;think&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;clever&quot;)
else:
    game.say(&quot;You freeze in panic.&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The player typed something not on the menu. What happens because of the <code>else</code>?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">actions = [&quot;fight&quot;, &quot;think&quot;, &quot;run&quot;]
game.say(f&quot;Choose: {actions[0]} / {actions[1]} / {actions[2]}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What menu line is printed?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, fix it on paper, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — Each action should give a <strong>different</strong> result. Right now "fight" and "think" print the same thing.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">action = game.ask(&quot;do?&quot;).strip().lower()
if action == &quot;fight&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You win the hard way!&quot;)
elif action == &quot;think&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You win the hard way!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the "think" branch should describe a clever win, not a brute-force one.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — There should be a catch-all for answers not on the menu. Right now an off-menu answer prints nothing at all.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">action = game.ask(&quot;fight / think&quot;).strip().lower()
if action == &quot;fight&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You attack!&quot;)
elif action == &quot;think&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You outsmart it!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> add an <code>else</code> for everything else.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — A wrong answer should get one retry before the game continues. Right now there is no second chance.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">actions = [&quot;fight&quot;, &quot;think&quot;, &quot;run&quot;]
action = game.ask(&quot;do what?&quot;).strip().lower()
if action not in actions:
    game.say(&quot;Pick from the menu.&quot;)
game.say(f&quot;You chose: {action}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> after the warning, ask again and store the new answer (reuse what you learned in week 7).</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Here is a working battle menu. Read it carefully and answer the questions below.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">actions = [&quot;fight&quot;, &quot;think&quot;, &quot;run&quot;]
game.say(f&quot;An enemy appears! Choose: {actions[0]} / {actions[1]} / {actions[2]}&quot;)
action = game.ask(&quot;What do you do?&quot;).strip().lower()
if action == &quot;fight&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You swing your sword and win the hard way!&quot;)
elif action == &quot;think&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You spot the enemy's weakness and win cleverly!&quot;)
elif action == &quot;run&quot;:
    game.say(&quot;You escape, but the enemy keeps your gold.&quot;)
else:
    game.say(&quot;You hesitate and get hit!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What is stored in the <code>actions</code> list, and how is it used to print the menu?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does this code use <code>elif</code> for "think" and "run" instead of three separate <code>if</code> statements?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Which line runs if the player types "dance"? Why?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>The <code>.strip().lower()</code> runs on the player's answer. What does it do, and why does it help the comparisons work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Each branch prints a different <code>outcome</code>. Name the outcome for "fight" and the outcome for "run".</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Explain Your Lesson Code 🎥</h2>
<p>Explain the battle menu code <strong>you</strong> wrote in today's live lesson. Record a short video on your phone (or a parent's phone). You may show it running. Teach it like the viewer has never coded, and try to use these words: <strong>action</strong>, <strong>menu</strong>, <strong>elif</strong>, <strong>else</strong>, <strong>outcome</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Show the menu your code prints and read out the actions on it.</li>
<li>Point to your <code>if</code> / <code>elif</code> / <code>else</code> and explain what each branch does.</li>
<li>Show what happens when the player types something off-menu, and explain why.</li>
<li>Explain why the order of your branches matters.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
